# Append these flags to the mtproto-proxy ExecStart line (same binary invocation),
# or merge into your wrapper script. Order does not matter for most flags.
# After edit: systemctl daemon-reload && systemctl restart mtproto.service
#
# IMPORTANT (mtproxy-0.02): if Linux PIDs exceed 65535 (common after long uptime with
# kernel.pid_max=4194304), the proxy aborts with:
#   init_common_PID: Assertion `!(p & 0xffff0000)' failed.
# Fix: reboot the VPS (resets PID counter), or use a patched MTProxy build; lowering
# pid_max below existing PIDs is not viable on a live system.
#
# Defaults in mtproxy-0.02 are aggressive on small VMs:
#   --msg-buffers-size 268435456  (256 MiB)
#   --cpu-threads 8, --io-threads 16
#
# Suggested coexistence with 3x-ui on ~1 vCPU / ~700 MiB RAM class VPS.
# Live snapshot (sofia): TCP inuse often 2.7k–3.4k+; nf_conntrack_count ~5k–8k / 131072;
# counters show heavy historical drop/early_drop — keep -c and accept-rate sane.

--msg-buffers-size 50331648
--cpu-threads 1
--io-threads 2
--nice 5

# Limit total accepted clients (raise if you need more; lowers conntrack pressure).
-c 10000

# Mitigate SYN/portscan storms sharing the same conntrack table as VPN.
--max-accept-rate 100

# If you use multiple -M workers, also cap per-worker special conns, e.g.:
# -C 2048
